              When most contractors think about theft losses, they focus on the replacement value of stolen equipment. However, the true cost extends far beyond the sticker price of a missing excavator or generator. Let's examine the complete financial impact:
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">1. Direct Equipment Losses</h3>

            <p class="mb-6">
              The most obvious cost is replacing stolen equipment. According to the National Crime Prevention Council:
            </p>

            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
              <li>Heavy equipment theft averages <strong>$30,000 per incident</strong></li>
              <li>Tool theft averages <strong>$5,000-10,000 per incident</strong></li>
              <li>Copper and material theft can exceed <strong>$50,000 per incident</strong></li>
              <li>The average construction site experiences <strong>3-5 theft incidents annually</strong></li>
            </ul>

            <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-600 p-6 my-8">
              <p class="font-semibold mb-2">Real-World Example:</p>
              <p>A Seattle contractor lost $180,000 in equipment over 6 months from a single project site. The losses included two skid steers ($70,000), copper wire ($40,000), and various tools ($70,000). Insurance covered only 60% after deductibles.</p>
            </div>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">2. Project Delays and Downtime</h3>

            <p class="mb-6">
              When critical equipment is stolen, projects grind to a halt. The ripple effects include:
            </p>

            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
              <li>Rental costs while waiting for replacement: <strong>$1,000-5,000/day</strong></li>
              <li>Labor costs for idle workers: <strong>$2,000-10,000/day</strong></li>
              <li>Liquidated damages for delays: <strong>$5,000-50,000/day</strong></li>
              <li>Lost productivity during recovery: <strong>20-30% for 2-4 weeks</strong></li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">3. Insurance Premium Increases</h3>

            <p class="mb-6">
              Multiple theft claims trigger significant premium increases:
            </p>

            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
              <li>First claim: <strong>15-25% premium increase</strong></li>
              <li>Second claim: <strong>30-50% increase</strong></li>
              <li>Third claim: <strong>Policy cancellation risk</strong></li>
              <li>Higher deductibles: <strong>$25,000-50,000 typical</strong></li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">4. Administrative and Legal Costs</h3>

